				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boogey-man23" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2362395); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2362395&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226144" alt="Boogey_Man23" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2362395)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/boogey-man23" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2362395); return false;" >Boogey_Man23</a></span> <span class="odate time_1515951097 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">14 Jan 2018 17:31</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3681927">
									

<p>I&#8230; am having a hard time pinning down just how I feel about this article.</p>
<p>Like others, I can see the parrallels it seems to draw with 'contemporary art' in the real world. If one looks, they can find plenty of debate on the talent / skill / creative merits of certain artworks or art forms; if they deserve to be called &quot;art&quot;; ultimately on what even is our definition of art. I think it's an interesting question, without necessarily any one correct answer.</p>
<p>But I reckon it's that line of thinking, of those questions raised, that might be the best part of the concept. I'll second the notion that maybe a tale would let you explore the angles more expansively, and likely be more directly engaging to the reader.</p>
<p>Though, one could argue that if this piece incites such thought and deep reflection in its audience then it is indeed high art&#8230; Hmmm, think I'll take a little time and a re-read before voting.</p>

							</div>

								
					
