																		I like its simplicity. It&#039;s a story!
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(637830); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=637830&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610226144" alt="SoullessSingularity" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=637830)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(637830); return false;" >SoullessSingularity</a></span> <span class="odate time_1516040511 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">15 Jan 2018 18:21</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3682789">
									

<p>I like its simplicity. It tells a story in a few paragraphs, which is well done and difficult to do, and many pieces can often be three times this length and say less than a third of what this is saying. It is a criticism of the current state of AWCY, in the same campy language exactly as you would expect from art descriptions. It captures the prose really well as expected from an overdramatic description of one's own art.</p>
<p>Here's a description of Rothko, aka, 'the guy that paints fuzzy rectangles'.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>One of the pioneers of Color Field Painting, Rothko’s abstract arrangements of shapes, ranging from the slightly surreal biomorphic ones in his early works to the dark squares and rectangles in later years, are intended to evoke the metaphysical through viewers’ communion with the canvas in a controlled setting.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I would argue that potentially the descriptions of ideas and arts that the artist was trying to convey should be a lot more evocative than they are now. There's a moment where you can reference other AWCY articles in the most exaggerated, over-the-top description possible, like the author is not only critiquing the AWCY world but is calling out other AWCY creators.</p>

							</div>

										<div class="signature">
					<hr class="signature-separator"/>
					

<p>Living the dream, or dreaming the life?</p>

				</div>
					
					
